force_capacity_tldr_en = "AU RTF forces succeeded in destroying several LRA camps and killing key commanders in 2013, while 16 Ugandan LRA combatants and 62 long-term women and children captives defected or escaped. Despite this, Kony retains firm control over the group's command structure and estimated 220 total fighters."
force_capacity_tldr_fr = "Les forces de l'UA RTF ont r&eacute;ussi &agrave; d&eacute;truire plusieurs camps de la LRA et &agrave; tuer des commandants cl&eacute;s en 2013, tandis que 16 combattants ougandais de la LRA et 62 femmes et enfants captifs &agrave; long terme ont fait d&eacute;fection ou se sont &eacute;chapp&eacute;s. Malgr&eacute; cela, Kony conserve un contr&ocirc;le ferme sur la structure de commandement du groupe et de ses environs 220 combattants au total.";

force_capacity_subtitle_1_en = "I. The LRA loses safe havens and key commanders"
force_capacity_text_1_en = "<p>In January 2013, Ugandan RTF troops in CAR <a href='http://blog.invisiblechildren.com/2013/01/21/top-lra-commander-killed-in-combat/' target='_blank'>killed Binany Okumu</a>, a Kony loyalist entrusted with ivory deliveries from Congo. In March, Ugandan RTF troops circumvented a Sudanese military garrison to destroy an LRA base in Kafia Kingi, missing Kony just days after he left for CAR. The Seleka coup in CAR then forced the AU RTF to put operations on hold, giving Kony new respite.</p><p>In September, operations gained new momentum as South Sudanese and Congolese RTF forces conducted their first offensive action against the LRA, utilizing substantial US military logistical and intelligence support. South Sudanese troops destroyed several LRA bases and fields in Congo's Garamba National Park, while Congolese troops destroyed an LRA base in Bas Uele district, including several acres of fields. In November, Ugandan troops <a href ='http://blog.invisiblechildren.com/2013/12/02/more-on-the-recent-lra-ambush-in-central-african-republic/' target='_blank'>killed LRA commander Samuel Kangul</a> and recovered supplies his group had attained from Central African authorities near Nzako. However, the <a href='http://reports.lracrisistracker.com/en/annual-2013/background/'>outbreak of civil war in South Sudan</a> and <a href='http://reports.lracrisistracker.com/en/annual-2013/background/'>deteriorating security in CAR</a> have once again put future AU RTF operations in jeopardy.</p> <p>Sixteen Ugandan LRA combatants defected in 2013. Most notably, <a href='http://blog.invisiblechildren.com/2013/12/10/breaking-news-largest-lra-defection-since-2008/' target='_blank'>senior LRA commander Lt. Col. Okello Okutti surrendered</a> in December in CAR with five other Ugandan combatants and 12 others. Nine of the Ugandan combatants who defected in 2013 reported being influenced by Come Home defection messaging, including Okutti's group. They cited Acholi-language programs run on the Uganda Broadcasting Corporation (UBC) station <a href='http://blog.invisiblechildren.com/2013/09/20/how-opondo-escaped-the-lra-after-15-years/' target='_blank'>as particularly influential</a> in encouraging them to defect.</p>"
force_capacity_text_1part2_en = "<p>In total, the LRA lost at least 32 Ugandan male combatants in 2013, with unconfirmed reports indicating Ugandan RTF troops killed or captured approximately eight more. Using baseline estimates from its 2013 report <i><a href='http://www.theresolve.org/2013/07/new-report-how-to-dismantle-the-lra-from-the-bottom-up/' target='_blank'>Loosening Kony's Grip</a></i>, The Resolve estimates that by the end of 2013 the LRA contained approximately 220 combatants, including an estimated 160-168 Ugandan officers and fighters and 50 non-Ugandan low-level fighters.</p>"
force_capacity_subtitle_1_fr = "I. La LRA perd ses lieux de refuges et des commandants cl&eacute;s";
force_capacity_text_1_fr = "<p>En janvier les troupes RTF Ougandaises en RCA ont <a href='http://blog.invisiblechildren.com/2013/01/21/top-lra-commander-killed-in-combat/' target='_blank'>tu&eacute; Binany Okumu</a>, un loyaliste de Kony charg&eacute; des livraisons d'ivoire venant du Congo. En mars, les troupes RTF Ougandaises ont contourn&eacute; une garnison militaire Soudanaise pour d&eacute;truire une base de la LRA dans le Kafia Kingi, manquant Kony de quelques jours apr&egrave;s son d&eacute;part pour la RCA. Le coup S&eacute;l&eacute;ka en RCA a forc&eacute; l'UA RTF &agrave; mettre ses op&eacute;rations en attente, donnant Kony nouveau r&eacute;pit.</p><p>En septembre, les op&eacute;rations ont pris un nouvel &eacute;lan alors que les forces RTF Sud-Soudanaises et Congolaises ont men&eacute; leur premi&egrave;re action offensive contre la LRA en utilisant un important soutien logistique et en renseignement de l&rsquo;arm&eacute;e Am&eacute;ricaine. Les troupes Sud-Soudanaises ont d&eacute;truit plusieurs bases et champs de la LRA dans le parc national de Garamba au Congo, tandis que les troupes Congolaises ont d&eacute;truit une base de la LRA dans le district du Bas U&eacute;l&eacute;, y compris plusieurs hectares de champs. En novembre, les troupes Ougandaises <a href ='http://blog.invisiblechildren.com/2013/12/02/more-on-the-recent-lra-ambush-in-central-african-republic/' target='_blank'>ont tu&eacute; le commandant LRA Samuel Kangul</a> et r&eacute;cup&eacute;r&eacute; des biens que son groupe avait obtenu des autorit&eacute;s de RCA pr&egrave;s de Nzako. Cependant, le <a href='http://reports.lracrisistracker.com/en/annual-2013/background/'>d&eacute;clenchement de la guerre civile au Sud-Soudan</a> et <a href='http://reports.lracrisistracker.com/en/annual-2013/background/'>la d&eacute;t&eacute;rioration de la s&eacute;curit&eacute; en RCA</a> ont une fois de plus mis les futures op&eacute;rations de l'UA RTF en danger.</p><p>Seize combattants ougandais de la LRA ont fait d&eacute;fection en 2013. Plus particuli&egrave;rement, <a href='http://blog.invisiblechildren.com/2013/12/10/breaking-news-largest-lra-defection-since-2008/' target='_blank'>le commandant sup&eacute;rieur de la LRA lieutenant-colonel Okello Okutti s&rsquo;est remis</a> en d&eacute;cembre en RCA avec cinq autres combattants Ougandais et 12 autres. Neuf des combattants Ougandais qui ont fait d&eacute;fection en 2013 ont d&eacute;clar&eacute; &ecirc;tre influenc&eacute; par des messages de d&eacute;fection ‘Come Home&rsquo;, y compris le groupe de Okutti.  Ils ont cit&eacute; les programmes de langue Acholi qui passent sur la station de la ‘Uganda Broadcasting Corporation&rsquo; (UBC) <a href='http://blog.invisiblechildren.com/2013/09/20/how-opondo-escaped-the-lra-after-15-years/' target='_blank'>comme particuli&egrave;rement influents</a> pour les encourager &agrave; faire d&eacute;fection.</p>";
force_capacity_text_1part2_fr = "<p>Au total, la LRA a perdu au moins 32 combattants hommes Ougandais en 2013, avec des rapports non confirm&eacute;s indiquant que les troupes RTF ougandaises en ont tu&eacute; ou captur&eacute; environ huit de plus. Utilisant des estimations de r&eacute;f&eacute;rence venant de son rapport de 2013 <i><a href='http://www.theresolve.org/2013/07/new-report-how-to-dismantle-the-lra-from-the-bottom-up/' target='_blank'>Desserrer la poigne de Kony</a></i>, Resolve estime que la LRA contenait environ 220 combattants, dont environ 160-168 officiers et combattants Ougandais et 50 combattants  non-Ougandais de bas niveau, &agrave; la fin de 2013.</p>";

