force_capacity_subtitle_2_en = "II. Kony's grip on the LRA command structure"
force_capacity_text_2_en = "<p>LRA founder Joseph Kony remains the group's undisputed leader, but below him the command hierarchy is in constant flux. Kony frequently promotes or demotes officers, often disregarding their conventional military rank, to ensure no commander attains enough influence to threaten his iron grip on the LRA. In recent years, Kony has <a href='http://www.lracrisistracker.com/command/evolution' target='_blank'>tended to promote younger commanders</a>. Many of them were abducted as young boys from northern Uganda and then served as his bodyguards and remain fiercely loyal to him. Kony has also reportedly empowered several of his sons, including Salim, an ambitious young officer raised in the bush. Meanwhile, Kony has demoted many older commanders who had military experience before joining the LRA, though his loyal second-in-command, Okot Odhiambo, retains a position of great influence.</p> <p>Kony's attempts to maintain his hold on power have come at significant risk and cost. He has authorized greater use of HF radios to maintain communications with far-flung LRA commanders, despite the danger that Ugandan military forces will use signal intercepts to track down LRA groups. Kony also reportedly <a href='http://www.theresolve.org/2013/07/new-report-how-to-dismantle-the-lra-from-the-bottom-up/' target='_blank'>ordered the execution of at least four LRA officers</a> for disobedience in late 2012 and early 2013. The most notable execution was of Otto Agweng, once one of Kony's most trusted and feared enforcers, after he raped a female captive against Kony's orders.</p> "
force_capacity_text_2_caption_en =  "<p>Kony's disciplinary actions, like his decisions on the command hierarchy, can be unpredictable. In 2012, Kony's half-brother David Olanya also incurred Kony's wrath for sleeping with a female captive without permission. However, Kony only demoted him, perhaps in deference to his family ties. Dominic Ongwen has also escaped the full force of Kony's justice, likely due to his family ties to Kony and bravery in battle.</p><p>Mapping the LRA's command structure is extremely difficult, given lack of access to the group and Kony's constant reshuffling of responsibilities. This graphic tracks the fates of 101 identified Ugandan officers who were confirmed members of the LRA as of 2009, providing a snapshot of how the command structure has fared since then.</p>"
force_capacity_subtitle_2_fr = "II. L'emprise de Kony sur la structure de commandement de la LRA";
force_capacity_text_2_fr = "<p>Le fondateur de la LRA Joseph Kony reste le leader incontest&eacute; du groupe, mais en dessous de lui la hi&eacute;rarchie de commande est en constante &eacute;volution. Kony fr&eacute;quemment promeut ou r&eacute;trograde des officiers, souvent sans consid&eacute;ration de leur grade militaire conventionnel, afin de veiller &agrave; ce qu'aucun commandant n&rsquo;atteigne assez d'influence pour menacer sa poigne de fer sur la LRA. Au cours des derni&egrave;res ann&eacute;es, Kony a <a href='http://www.lracrisistracker.com/command/evolution' target='_blank'>tendance &agrave; favoriser les commandants les plus jeunes</a>. Beaucoup de ces commandants ont &eacute;t&eacute; enlev&eacute;s comme jeunes gar&ccedil;ons depuis le nord de l'Ouganda, et ont ensuite servi comme ses gardes du corps et lui demeurent tr&egrave;s fid&egrave;les. Kony aurait &eacute;galement habilit&eacute; plusieurs de ses fils, y compris Salim, un jeune officier ambitieux &eacute;lev&eacute; dans la brousse. Pendant ce temps, Kony a r&eacute;trograd&eacute; de nombreux commandants plus &acirc;g&eacute;s qui ont eu une exp&eacute;rience militaire avant de rejoindre la LRA, bien que son fid&egrave;le second de commande, Okot Odhiambo, conserve une position de grande influence.</p><p>Les tentatives de Kony pour maintenir son emprise sur le pouvoir sont venus &agrave; risques et co&ucirc;ts importants. Il a autoris&eacute; une plus grande utilisation des radios &agrave; haute fr&eacute;quence (HF) afin de maintenir les communications avec les commandants de la LRA &eacute;loign&eacute;s, malgr&eacute; le danger que les forces militaires Ougandaises vont utiliser les interceptions de signaux pour traquer les groupes de la LRA. Kony aurait &eacute;galement <a href='http://www.theresolve.org/2013/07/new-report-how-to-dismantle-the-lra-from-the-bottom-up/' target='_blank'>ordonn&eacute; l'ex&eacute;cution d'au moins quatre officiers de la LRA</a> pour d&eacute;sob&eacute;issance &agrave; la fin de 2012 et d&eacute;but 2013. L'ex&eacute;cution la plus notable &eacute;tait celle d&rsquo;Otto Agweng, autre fois l'un des ex&eacute;cutants les plus fiables et les plus craints de Kony, apr&egrave;s qu&rsquo;il ait viol&eacute; une femme captive contre les ordres de Kony.</p>";
force_capacity_text_2_caption_fr =  "<p>Les mesures disciplinaires de Kony, comme ses d&eacute;cisions sur la hi&eacute;rarchie de commande, peuvent &ecirc;tre impr&eacute;visibles. En 2012, le demi-fr&egrave;re David Olanya de Kony a &eacute;galement engag&eacute; la col&egrave;re de Kony pour avoir couch&eacute; avec une femme captive sans autorisation. Cependant, Kony l&rsquo;a seulement r&eacute;trograd&eacute;, peut-&ecirc;tre par respect pour ses liens familiaux. Dominic Ongwen a &eacute;galement &eacute;chapp&eacute; &agrave; la force de la justice de Kony, probablement en raison de ses liens familiaux &agrave; Kony et sa bravoure au combat.</p><p>Cartographier la structure de commandement de la LRA est extr&ecirc;mement difficile, &eacute;tant donn&eacute; le manque d'acc&egrave;s au groupe et le remaniement constant des responsabilit&eacute;s par Kony.  Ce graphique suit les destins de 101 officiers Ougandais identifi&eacute;s qui ont &eacute;t&eacute; des membres confirm&eacute;s de la LRA &agrave; partir de 2009, donnant un aper&ccedil;u de la fa&ccedil;on dont la structure de commandement a chang&eacute; depuis lors.</p>"

force_capacity_subtitle_3_en = "III. Long-term women and children captives return home"
force_capacity_text_3_en = "<p>While male Ugandan officers monopolize power within the LRA, they depend on women and children held in long-term captivity to survive on a day-to-day basis. Women and children set up and take down camps, transport camp essentials when groups move, cook, and perform other essential duties. Many women and girls are forced into sexual relationships with male officers and fighters. Occasionally women participate in looting raids, and a few have become officers.</p> <p>At the beginning of 2013, the LRA had approximately 250 women and children within its ranks, including both long-term captives who had been with the LRA for over six months and short-term abductees. Sixty-two women and children held in long-term captivity escaped the LRA in 2013, a majority of which (32) were children originally abducted from CAR, Congo, or South Sudan. Ten Ugandan women and children long-term captives escaped the LRA in 2013, a slight reduction from the 13 who escaped in 2012. Nearly 75% of the 62 returnees were <a href='http://blog.invisiblechildren.com/2013/04/01/update-on-the-28-women-and-children-who-escaped-the-lra-last-week/' target='_blank'>intentionally released by the LRA</a> or escaped with an LRA combatant, indicating that the LRA may have trouble feeding women and children and may have less utility for them as the number of combatants dwindles. Only seven of the 62 returnees escaped on their own, suggesting women and children have inadequate information, opportunities, and incentives to escape.</p>"
force_capacity_subtitle_3_fr = "III. Les femmes et enfants captifs &agrave; long terme rentrent chez eux";
force_capacity_text_3_fr = "<p>Bien que les officiers Ougandais hommes monopolisent le pouvoir au sein de la LRA, ils d&eacute;pendent sur les femmes et les enfants d&eacute;tenus en captivit&eacute; &agrave; long terme pour survivre au jour le jour. Les femmes et les enfants mettent en place et d&eacute;montent les camps, transportent les essentiels de campement lorsque les groupes se d&eacute;placent, cuisinent, et accomplissent d'autres t&acirc;ches essentielles. Beaucoup de femmes et de filles sont contraintes &agrave; des relations sexuelles avec des officiers masculins et les combattants. Parfois les femmes participent au pillage des raids, et quelques-unes ont &eacute;t&eacute; promues au niveau d&rsquo;officier.</p><p>Au d&eacute;but de 2013, la LRA avait environ 250 femmes et enfants dans ses rangs, y compris les captifs &agrave; long terme qui avaient &eacute;t&eacute; avec la LRA pour plus de six mois ainsi que les personnes enlev&eacute;es &agrave; court terme. Soixante-deux femmes et enfants d&eacute;tenus en captivit&eacute; &agrave; long terme ont &eacute;chapp&eacute; &agrave; la LRA en 2013, dont la majorit&eacute; (32) &eacute;taient des enfants enlev&eacute;s &agrave; l'origine de la RCA, du Congo, ou du Sud-Soudan. Dix femmes et enfants Ougandais captifs &agrave; long terme ont &eacute;chapp&eacute; &agrave; la LRA en 2013, une l&eacute;g&egrave;re diminution des 13 qui se sont &eacute;chapp&eacute;s en 2012. Pr&egrave;s de 75% des 62 rapatri&eacute;s ont &eacute;t&eacute; <a href='http://blog.invisiblechildren.com/2013/04/01/update-on-the-28-women-and-children-who-escaped-the-lra-last-week/' target='_blank'>volontairement lib&eacute;r&eacute;s par la LRA</a> ou se sont &eacute;chapp&eacute;s avec un combattant de la LRA, ce qui indique que la LRA peut avoir du mal &agrave; nourrir les femmes et les enfants et peut avoir moins d'utilit&eacute; pour eux alors que le nombre de combattants diminue. Seulement sept des 62 rapatri&eacute;s se sont &eacute;chapp&eacute;s seuls, ce qui sugg&egrave;re que les femmes et les enfants ont des informations, possibilit&eacute;s et incitations &agrave; s'&eacute;chapper insuffisantes.</p>";

